Yes — do it one at a time, but I would slightly change the order:

1. Add Graviton nodes
2. Test Sensu ARM image with backend or canary agent
3. Convert/update assets to ARM64
4. Move Sensu agents to ARM64
5. Remove AMD64 scheduling

Do not move all Sensu agents to ARM first and then fix assets. Your checks will likely fail because your assets are still AMD64-only.

Recommended sequence

Step 1 — Add Graviton nodes

Add ARM64 node group/Karpenter capacity, preferably tainted:

taints:
  - key: graviton
    value: "true"
    effect: NoSchedule

This prevents accidental scheduling.


---

Step 2 — Change Sensu image to multi-arch/ARM-compatible

Use a multi-arch Sensu image, for example:

image: sensu/sensu:<validated-version>

Do not force an ARM64 digest yet unless you are sure. If the image is multi-arch, Kubernetes will pull the correct architecture based on the node.

Test:

docker buildx imagetools inspect sensu/sensu:<version>

You want to see:

linux/amd64
linux/arm64


---

Step 3 — Move only the Sensu backend first

This is usually safer than moving agents first.

Patch backend only:

nodeSelector:
  kubernetes.io/arch: arm64

tolerations:
  - key: graviton
    operator: Equal
    value: "true"
    effect: NoSchedule

Then validate:

kubectl get pods -n <sensu-namespace> -o wide
kubectl logs -n <sensu-namespace> deploy/sensu-backend
sensuctl cluster health
sensuctl entity list

But note: if your handlers/mutators use runtime assets, those assets must also support ARM64 before backend migration.


---

Step 4 — Do not move agents yet

Agents run most checks. Since your check assets are currently AMD64-only, ARM agents will register, but checks using those assets may fail.

So keep agents on AMD64 temporarily while you convert assets:

nodeSelector:
  kubernetes.io/arch: amd64

This is still a phased migration, not the final state.


---

Step 5 — Convert assets one by one

For each asset:

http-check
aggregate-check
aws-sns-handler
cloudwatch-check
plugins-aws
plugins-http
ruby-runtime

Add ARM64 builds under the same asset names.

Example:

type: Asset
api_version: core/v2
metadata:
  name: http-check
spec:
  builds:
    - url: <amd64-url>
      sha512: <amd64-sha>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'amd64'

    - url: <arm64-url>
      sha512: <arm64-sha>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'

Your checks stay unchanged:

runtime_assets:
  - http-check


---

Step 6 — Move Sensu agents to Graviton

Only after all required assets have ARM64 builds, patch the agent DaemonSet:

nodeSelector:
  kubernetes.io/arch: arm64

tolerations:
  - key: graviton
    operator: Equal
    value: "true"
    effect: NoSchedule

Then validate:

kubectl get pods -n <sensu-namespace> -o wide
sensuctl entity list
sensuctl event list
kubectl logs -n <sensu-namespace> daemonset/sensu-agent

Look for asset errors like:

no matching asset build
exec format error
failed to fetch asset


---

So your proposed order?

> First image in ARM. If it works, then move assets.



I would adjust it to:

First: Sensu image + backend on ARM
Second: Convert assets
Third: Sensu agents on ARM

Because the backend image can prove Sensu itself runs on Graviton. But agents should not move until assets are ARM-ready.

Final recommended STG order

1. Add Graviton nodes with taint.
2. Use ARM64/multi-arch Sensu image.
3. Move backend to ARM64.
4. Validate backend.
5. Add ARM64 asset builds.
6. Move agents to ARM64.
7. Validate all checks/events.
8. Remove AMD64 dependency.

That gives you a clean, low-risk path to Graviton-only without breaking all checks at once.